        <trans-unit id="103" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>This example shows how to create a 3-D object that looks like a flat sheet of paper which has been rotated.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Controls.Viewport3D&gt;</ph> along with the following components are used to create this simple 3-D scene:</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A camera is created using a <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.PerspectiveCamera&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The camera specifies what part of the 3-D scene is viewable.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A mesh is created to specify the shape of 3-D object (sheet of paper) using the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.GeometryModel3D.Geometry%2A&gt;</ph> property of <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.GeometryModel3D&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A material is specified to be displayed on the surface of the object (linear gradient in this sample) using the <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.GeometryModel3D.Material%2A&gt;</ph> property of <ph id="ph2">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.GeometryModel3D&gt;</ph>.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>A light is created to shine on the object using <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Windows.Media.Media3D.DirectionalLight&gt;</ph>.</source>
